Chapter 10: Project Architect
The Old Library was a graveyard of paper. In an age of holographic data-slates and direct-brain downloads, the smell of decaying parchment was an anomaly. The Association ignored this wing; to them, if information wasn't digital, it didn't exist.
Ren moved through the shadows of the towering mahogany shelves, his footsteps muffled by a thick layer of dust.
[Passive Activated: Absolute Zero]
[Detection Risk: 0.02%]
The silver geometric pattern on his wrist pulsed with a faint, rhythmic heat. As he approached the back of the room, a section of the air flickered.
"Scanning..." a tiny, mechanical voice whispered.
A hidden security eye, no larger than a marble, swiveled toward him. Ren didn't freeze. He looked directly at the lens. In his vision, the red laser wasn't a beam of light—it was a string of binary permissions.
[Skill Trigger: Source Code Redirection]
[Action: Insert 'Authorized' Tag into Buffer.]
The eye blinked green and returned to its dormant state. Ren reached the row of lockers Aris had mentioned. He inserted the brass key into locker #000. It turned with a heavy, metallic clunk.
Inside was a single, leather-bound folder. The cover was stamped with the Academy’s original seal—a Gate intertwined with a DNA helix—and a bold red stamp: TERMINATED.
Ren opened the folder.
"Project Architect," he whispered, reading the first page.
Subject: Artificial Creation of a "Clean" Interface.
Hypothesis: Current Hunters are limited by their 'Affinity'. Their power is a filter provided by the Void. To truly control the Gates, we need a vessel with 0.00% Affinity—a blank slate capable of rewriting the Void's logic instead of just channeling it.
Ren flipped the page. There were sketches of a child—a boy with silver eyes.
Log 44: The subject, Ren, shows no response to Essence exposure. Success. He is 'invisible' to the system. However, the Board fears he cannot be controlled. If he awakens the 'Source Code', he will not be a Hunter. He will be the Administrator.
"I wasn't admitted," Ren muttered, the paper trembling in his hand. "I was grown."
[Alert: High-Level Essence Signature Detected. Proximity: 5 meters.]
"It’s a lot to take in, isn't it?"
Ren spun around, slamming the folder shut.
Kaelen was standing at the end of the aisle. He looked different. His white uniform had been replaced by a sleek, black combat suit with gold circuitry. His eyes weren't just glowing; they were burning with a violent, purple intensity.
"Kaelen," Ren said, hiding the folder behind his back. "You’re supposed to be at your promotion ceremony."
"I was," Kaelen said. His voice had a strange, echoing quality. "The 'Upgrade' was... enlightening. I can see so much more now, Ren. I can see the vibrations in the air. I can see the heat coming off your skin. And I can see that mark on your hand."
Kaelen took a step forward. The floorboards beneath his feet charred black.
"The Association told me to find the 'Anomaly' that stole the data at Site 9," Kaelen continued. "They said whoever has it is a threat to the world. But they didn't tell me it was my own classmate."
"Kaelen, listen to me," Ren said, his mind racing. "The upgrade... it’s a parasite. The Association is using you to track me because they can't see me themselves."
"A parasite?" Kaelen laughed, and the sound made the glass in the library windows crack. "I’ve never felt more powerful. I’m an S-Rank now, Ren. I’m the hero the world needs. And heroes have to eliminate bugs."
Kaelen raised his hand. A sphere of purple fire, dense as a star, formed in his palm.
[Target: Kaelen (Ascended)]
[Status: Controlled/Overclocked]
[Danger Level: FATAL]
"Give me the folder, Ren," Kaelen said, his voice dropping to a low, distorted growl. "And maybe I’ll tell them you were just a victim."
Ren looked at the silver mark on his hand. It was glowing brighter than Kaelen’s fire.
[Notification: 'The Administrator' is watching.]
[New Objective: Defeat the S-Rank 'Hero'.]
[Reward: Unlock 'Void Path' Skill: 'Logic Blade'.]
"I'm not a victim, Kaelen," Ren said, dropping the folder and stepping into a combat stance he had never practiced, but his body suddenly knew. "And you’re not a hero. You're just a puppet."
The purple fire erupted, turning the Old Library into an oven.
The first true fight between the "Artificial Hero" and the "Natural Bug" has begun.
